Please use common sense. Talk to the person on the phone first and meet in safe place where both of you can smile at the security cameras.

title: For Sale/Trade:  M1 GARAND 1944 SPRINGFIELD ARMORY, 1000 rd AMMO, more
postcontent:
I will start by describing the rifle, then the ammo.

In the attached photos: the rifle for sale has the darker blue/black finish, the other rifle is just for comparison with a typical Garand finish.

I’ve gone to gun shows since I grew up in the 60’s but I am not an expert on Garands. Like most all Garands this one has been rebuilt, but apparently in Great Britain, due to the British proof marks, black British-style finish, and several British-style repairs to the handguard.

This rifle is a CAI import, they do not seem to have a good reputation on the internet. CAI seems to be accused of using bad, even rewelded receivers. However, my rifle has an excellent condition, original Springfield Armory receiver which dates to early February, 1944. The barrel is marked SA 2-44 and must be the original barrel, unfortunately it is pitted and has muzzle wear. If you are fanatical about barrel condition or want the rifle for target shooting this is probably not your best choice in a Garand. (At least it is the original barrel.)

The stock is very nice, with a clear circle-P marking and the remains of the outline of a cartouche box. The inside of the stock is marked “OR” apparently, and possibly the numbers 3312.

These parts are SA: hammer, trigger housing, bolt, receiver, barrel.

Trigger guard: WRA 46025.

Op rod HRA 6535382.

It seems there are several possible uses for this rifle:
•	Keep and value the rifle as-is, representing a “British arsenal commercial rework” variation of the Garand rifle.
•	Keep and value the rifle as-is for casual shooting, as a historical relic, an investment (future imports may be banned) and even now as a reliable, hard-hitting weapon.
•	Take the rifle apart and apportion the parts as they best help your collection.
•	Keep the ammo, see below, sell or trade the rifle in the future.

Now about the ammo:

This package includes 1000 rounds of clean, shiny military surplus ammo with sealed primers. Of the 1000 rounds, 720 are Greek 30-06 ball; the remaining 280 rounds are black tip FN A/P.

Of these 1000 rounds, 840 rounds are already loaded into 8-round Garand clips, 280 rounds into each of 3 vintage ammo cans. (105 loaded 8-round clips=840 rounds.)

One can is fully loaded with Fabrique Nationale black tip A/P ammo on clips, here is a possible retail value for this one can of ammo: 280 rounds @ $1.50 each, 35 clips @ $3 each, $20 for vintage ammo can, total $545.

To approximate the retail price the Greek ball, 720 rounds @ $1 each, 2 more ammo cans @ $20 each, 70 more clips @ $3 each, total $970.
